THE RISK (context, do not rewrite): perturbation [{"nodeId":"serviceableFactor","op":"set","value":0.38,"note":"Regulatory haircut plus DCIM/API integration-locked replacement sockets removed from reachable scope — below the model's 0.45 low edge"}], likelihood 0.3, category fact

FIELDS TO REWRITE:
{
 "title": "Legrand's dual ownership of Raritan and Server Technology makes the intelligent-PDU sub-market far more closed than the 0.55 whole-market CR3 suggests",
 "narrative": "The ledger's CR3 of 0.55 is extrapolated from whole-PDU-market data and even the digest treats Raritan and Server Technology as separate 'top players' — but both belong to Legrand. In the intelligent-PDU sub-market where this venture actually plays, one owner controls the two pioneering brands whose outlet-level monitoring APIs are wired into operators' DCIM and monitoring stacks, alongside Vertiv (Geist) and Schneider with their own DCIM suites. That changes the nature of the serviceable market: the enterprise (29%) and colocation (18%) replacement sockets that a Year-1 entrant must live off are not vendor-neutral — swapping the PDU means re-integrating the monitoring layer, so incumbents win renewals without a selection event. The 0.55 serviceable factor treats regulatory reach as the only haircut; the software-integration lock quietly removes another tranche of TAM from anyone's reach but the incumbents'.",
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "The CR3 estimate rests on whole-PDU data and a single 15.8% Schneider datapoint, while Credence lists Server Technology and Raritan as separate top players — masking that Legrand owns both intelligent-PDU pioneer brands, so intelligent-PDU concentration is materially higher than the whole-market 0.55 proxy",
   "refs": [
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c5",
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c0",
    "ledger:shape.cr3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Intelligent PDUs are purchased as endpoints of DCIM/monitoring stacks; installed bases in the enterprise and colocation segments — the venture's realistic Year-1 sockets — are standardized on incumbent APIs and management suites, so replacement demand renews with the incumbent without a competitive evaluation",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:seg.enterprise",
    "ledger:seg.colocation",
    "profile:Product"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The serviceable haircut (0.55) was justified only by the EU certification stack and carries no integration-lock component; adding the DCIM-locked share of replacement demand pushes the truly serviceable fraction below the model's 0.45 low edge",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:serviceableFactor",
    "digest:cr3-vendors#c1"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "Two separate camouflages stack: the vendor lists the team read name Raritan and Server Technology as distinct competitors (so the intelligent-PDU duopoly-under-one-roof never registers), and serviceableFactor was framed as a regulatory/channel haircut, so software-integration lock was never on the list of things that could shrink it. No source publishes sub-market shares — the Omdia table that would reveal this is paywalled — so the whole-market proxy passed unchallenged.",
 "falsifier": "The Omdia 2025 rack-PDU vendor-share table showing intelligent-PDU sub-segment concentration at or below the whole-market level — or CE operator interviews confirming that open protocols (SNMP/Redfish) make mixing PDU vendors within an existing DCIM stack a routine, low-friction decision.",
 "likelihoodRationale": "Legrand's dual-brand ownership is fact and DCIM integration stickiness is well documented qualitatively, but the actual locked fraction of CE replacement demand is unquantified — no source publishes sub-market shares or switching-cost data, so the magnitude rests on judgment [evidence revision: The dual-ownership fact is confirmed and the merged Legrand platform reinforces the concentration argument, raising confidence in the trigger step. But the load-bearing propagation step rests on integration-lock magnitude, which is actively countered by mature open standards (Redfish DSP2056 for power equipment, SNMP drivers) and vendor-neutral DCIM normalization, plus Mordor's independent 'Medium' concentration rating. The falsifier's second clause (open protocols make mixing routine) has partial support, so the net serviceable-TAM impact is weaker than posited. Modest downward revision from 0.35 to 0.30.]"
}

